'''''Arctoscopus japonicus''''', the '''sailfin sandfish''' or '''Japanese sandfish''', is a species of fish of the [[Perciformes]] (Perch-likes) order, [[Trichodontidae]] (sandfishes) family. Known in Japan as {{nihongo||<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF>, <U+9C30>, <U+9C69>, <U+71ED><U+9B5A>|hatahata}}, it is a commercially important fish especially for [[Akita Prefecture|Akita]] and [[Yamagata Prefecture|Yamagata]] prefectures.<ref name="masuda"/> Its habitat occurs in sandy-mud [[Benthic fish|bottoms]] ranging from the [[Sea of Japan]] to the [[Okhotsk Sea]].<ref name="fishbase"/>

As a food source, the fish has mostly been locally, in the coastal region of the Sea of Japan, and has been designated the official prefectural fish of [[Akita Prefecture]]<ref name="makino"/> The fish, which is scaleless, may be prepared whole as braised or grilled fish, and has a mucilagenous consistency.<ref name="lowry"/> It is also into ''himono'' ([[stockfish]]), salted, or cured in [[miso]] as ''misozuke''. It is also the ingredient of the [[fish sauce]] called ''[[shottsuru]]''.<ref name="homma"/> The egg masses are known as ''burikko''.<ref name="homma"/> In Korean the fish is called {{linktext|<U+B3C4>|<U+B8E8>|<U+BB35>}} ''dorumuk''.<ref name="fishbase"/>

The fish had also been used dried or in fish meal form as fertilizer, and shipped to agricultural areas at one time, into the 20th century.

== Life cycle and behavior==
Its life span is 5 years,<ref name="makino"/> attaining a typical [[fork length]] of 20&nbsp;cm.<ref name="kim-lee-cha">{{citation|last1=Kim|first1=Chang Gil|last2=Lee|first2=Sung Il|last3=Cha|first3=Hyung Kee|others=Jae Hyeong Yang and Yong Soo Son|contribution=Enhancement of Sandfish, Arctoscopus japonicus, by Artificial Reefs in the Eastern Waters of Korea|work=Artificial Reefs in Fisheries Management|publisher=CRC Press|year=2011|pages=111&ndash;|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=-L5nva1nXvsC&pg=PA111|isbn=1439820082}}</ref> It is a [[deep sea fish]] that usually inhahabits sandy and muddy sea floors in waters of 200 to 400 meters (550 meters<ref name="fishbase50550">Fedorov, V.V., I.A. Chereshnev, M.V. Nazarkin, A.V. Shestakov and V.V. Volobuev, 2003. Catalog of marine and freswater fishes of the northern part of the Sea of Okhotsk. Vladivostok: Dalnauka, 2003. 204 p.</ref>) below surface, but migrate from November to January to spawn in shallow rocky beds of seaweed.<ref name="kim-lee-cha"/> The male reaches sexual maturity at 1 1/2 year of age and beyond, and females at the 2 year-old stage; they do not die after spawning and run the course of several breeding cycles.<ref name="makino"/><ref name="makino">{{citation|last=Makino|first=Mitsutaku|title=Fisheries Management in Japan: Its institutional features and case studies|publisher=Springer|year=2011|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jfAqoA1D7loC&pg=PA178|page=178|isbn=9400717776}}</ref><ref>{{PDFlink|[http://abchan.job.affrc.go.jp/digests24/details/2449.pdf <U+5E73><U+6210> 24 <U+5E74><U+5EA6><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+65E5><U+672C><U+6D77><U+5317><U+90E8><U+7CFB><U+7FA4><U+306E><U+8CC7><U+6E90><U+8A55><U+4FA1>]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Tomoda|first1=Tsutomu|last2=Hotta|first2=Kazuo|last3=Morioka|first3=Taizo|title=Growth, spawning and migration of hatchery-reared Japanese sandfish Arctoscopus japonicus released in Nanao Bay and Toyama Bay|journal=Nippon Suisan Gakkaishi|volume=72(6)|pages=1039<U+2013>1045|doi=10.2331/suisan.72.1039}} [http://www.researchgate.net/publication/250157719_Growth_spawning_and_migration_of_hatchery-reared_Japanese_sandfish_Arctoscopus_japonicus_released_in_Nanao_Bay_and_Toyama_Bay abstract]</ref>

It preys and feeds on [[Amphipoda|amphipods]], [[copepod]]s, [[mysidacea]], krill, squid, and fish.<ref name="makino"/><ref>{{citation|last1=Komoto|first1=Ryota (<U+7532><U+672C><U+4EAE><U+592A>)|last2=Kudo|first2=Yuki (<U+5DE5><U+85E4><U+88D5><U+7D00>)|last3=Takatsu|first3=Tetsuya (<U+9AD9><U+6D25><U+54F2><U+4E5F>)|title=Vertical distribution and feeding habits of Japanese sandfish (Arctoscopus japonicus) larvae and juveniles off Akita Prefecture in the Sea of Japan|journal=<U+6C34><U+7523><U+5897><U+6B96> (Suisan z<U+014D>shoku)|volume=59|number=4|year=2011|pages=615&ndash;630|url=http://hdl.handle.net/2115/51002}} [http://eprints.lib.hokudai.ac.jp/dspace/handle/2115/51002 abstract]</ref>

=== Distribution ===
It is distributed in the northwestern [[Pacific Ocean]], particularly [[Sea of Japan]] to the [[Okhotsk Sea]], [[Kurile Islands]]  and [[Kamchatka Peninsula]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Okiyama|1990}}; cited in {{Harvnb|Shibata|1993|p=17}}</ref>

Three broad regional population groups had been postulated by Okiyama (1970) based on tagging,<ref>{{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Okiyama|first1=M. (<U+6C96><U+5C71><U+5B97><U+96C4>)|title=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+306E><U+8CC7><U+6E90><U+751F><U+7269><U+5B66><U+7684><U+7814><U+7A76>.II<U+7CFB><U+7D71><U+7FA4>(<U+4E88><U+5831>)|journal=<U+65E5><U+672C><U+6D77><U+533A><U+6C34><U+7523><U+7814><U+7A76><U+6240><U+7814><U+7A76><U+5831><U+544A>|volume=22|pages=59<U+2013>69}}, cited by {{Harvnb|Shirai|Kurnanaga|Sugiyama|Higuchi|2006|p=357}}</ref> and later [[mitochondrial DNA]] analysis confirmed these grouping on a genetic basis.<ref>Finding in {{Harvnb|Shirai|Kurnanaga|Sugiyama|Higuchi|2006}}, summarized in {{Harvnb|Shirai|Goto|Hirose|2007|p=47}} (latter is in Japanese)</ref> The population groups are:<ref>{{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Shirai|first1=Shigeru M.|last2=Kuranaga|first2=Ryoji|last3=Sugiyama|first3=Hideki|last4=Higuchi|first4=Masahito|title=Population structure of the sailfin sandfish, Arcto scopus japonicus (Trichodontidae), in the Sea of Japan|journal=Ichthyological Research|volume=53|year=2006|pages=357<U+2013>368|url=http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10228-006-0356-0#page-1}}</ref><ref name="A_PR54_47">{{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Shirai|first1=S. M. (<U+767D><U+4E95><U+8302>)|last2=Goto|first2=Tomoaki (<U+5F8C><U+85E4><U+53CB><U+660E>)|last3=Hirose|first3=Taro (<U+5EE3><U+702C><U+592A><U+90CE>)|title=2004<U+5E74>2-3<U+6708><U+306B><U+5F97><U+3089><U+308C><U+305F><U+5CA9><U+624B><U+6C96><U+306E><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+306F><U+65E5><U+672C><U+6D77><U+304B><U+3089><U+6765><U+904A><U+3057><U+305F>|journal=<U+9B5A><U+985E><U+5B66><U+96D1><U+8A8C>|volume=54|number=1|year=2007|pages=47<U+2013>58|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/jji1950/54/1/54_1_47/_article/-char/ja/}}</ref>

* Western Japan (WJ) -  Group that migrate the coast of the [[Sea of Japan]] from [[Tottori Prefecture|Tottori]] to Akita Prefecture. Comprised of the "northern Sea of Japan" and "western Sea of Japan" subgroups.<ref>{{cite web|ref=harv|url=http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10228-006-0356-0#page-1|last=Shirai|first=Shigeru M. (<U+767D><U+4E95><U+6ECB>)|title=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF> <U+65E5><U+672C><U+6D77><U+897F><U+90E8><U+7CFB><U+7FA4><U+306E><U+7531><U+6765> (<U+4E88><U+5831>)|journal=Ichthyological Research|year=2009|url=http://jsnfri.fra.affrc.go.jp/kenkyu/ronbun/H19ronbun/shuuroku-43,30-31.pdf}} [http://aquadb.fra.affrc.go.jp/~aquadb/cgi-bin/speciesinfo.cgi?LANG=jp&TTAXID=148607&TARGET=1 pdf (alternate site)]</ref><ref name="watanabe">{{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Watanabe|first1=Kyuji|last2=Sakuramoto|first2=Kazumi|last3=Minami|first3=Takashi|last4=Suzuki|first4=Naoki|title=Population structure of the sailfin sandfish, Arcto scopus japonicus (Trichodontidae), in the Sea of Japan|journal=Bull. Jpn. Soc. Fish. Oceanogr.|volume=70|number=4|year=2006|pages=221&ndash;228|url=http://jsfo.jp/contents/pdf/70-4-221.pdf}}</ref> The spawning grounds of the group has been assumed to be off all along the coast, but bulk spawning grounds are absent around the Noto Peninsula and any further west/south,{{citation needed|March-2014|date=April 2014}} and in fact, it has been reported that the western Sea of Japan group's spawning grounds occur in the east coast of the Korean peninsula.<ref>Choi et al., 1983, cited in {{Harvnb|Watanabe|Sakuramoto|Minami|Suzuki|2006|p=221}}</ref>

* South Hokkaido (SH) -  Group with breeding grounds in the Pacific Ocean off Hokkaido. Consists of {{ill2|Ishikari Bay|ja|<U+77F3><U+72E9><U+6E7E>}}, {{ill2|Uchiura Bay{{!}}Funka Bay|ja|<U+5674><U+706B><U+6E7E>}}, [[Hidaka Subprefecture|Hidaka]], [[Kushiro, Hokkaido|Kushiro]], and [[Nemuro, Hokkaido|Nemuro]] subgroups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fishexp.hro.or.jp/cont/marine/o7u1kr0000001nz9-att/10hatahata.pdf|title=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+306E><U+751F><U+304D><U+6B8B><U+308A><U+6761><U+4EF6><U+3092><U+63A2><U+308B>|author=Resources Management Division of the Kushiro {{ill2|fisheries experimental station|ja|<U+6C34><U+7523><U+8A66><U+9A13><U+5834>}} of Kurshiro|year=2006|accessdate=March-2014}}</ref>
* Eastern Korea (EK)  - with breeding grounds in the Eastern coast of the Korean Peninsula.

Catch production in the [[T<U+014D>hoku region]] (Northeastern Japan)'s Pacific coast (otherwise known as "[[Sanriku]]") is modest, and no regular spawning grounds have been confirmed.<ref name="A_PR54_47"/> Migration routes have not be charted, but their travel range is considered extensive, since individuals from the Hokkaido and Sea of Japan population groups have been captured in the Sanriku shore.<ref name="A_PR54_47"/>

=== External morphology ===
The color is silvery underneath, and light brown above with dark brown streaks flecked with spots.<ref name=smithsonian>{{cite journal|last1=Jordan|first1= David Starr|last2=Evermann|first2=Barton Warren|title=A Review of the Trachinoid Fishes and their Supposed Allies found in the Waters of Japan|journal=Proceedings of the United States National Museum|volume=24|year=1902|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=KL0oAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA484|page=484}}</ref> Tall body depth, though not as high as the Pacific sandfish (''[[Trichodon trichodon]]'').<ref name="shibata"/> Head and trunk are scaleless<ref>{{cite book|last=Jordan|first=David Starr|title=Fishes|publisher=Henry Holt|year=1907|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=u71hAd_B1KcC&pg=PA578|page=578}}</ref><ref name="chereshnev">{{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Chereshnev|first1=I. A.|last2=Nazarki|first2=M. V.|title=On the occurrence of Japanese sandfish Arctoscopus japonicus (Trichodontidae) in the region of Tauisk Bay of the Sea of Okhotsk|journal=Journal of Ichthyology|volume=42|year=2006|pages=683&ndash;686|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=AtTzAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>

A large mouth, oblique and turned upwards, is lined with rows of fine teeth.<ref name="chereshnev"/> The gill-flap on the cheek ([[preopercle]]) each has five sharp spines.<ref name=smithsonian/> It has a first dorsal and a second dorsal fin that are  separated by a gap.<ref name=smithsonian/> The [[pectoral fin]]s are particularly large.<ref name=smithsonian/> The [[Swim bladder|air-bladder]] is absent,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Boulenger|first=G.A.|title=Classification of Teleostean Fishes|journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History: Zoology, Botany, and Geology|series=7|volume=8|year=1901|page=269|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PqM0AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA269}}</ref> Active nocturnally, during the day time it lies buried in the mud or sand on the bottom, with only the mouth and eyes (and the spine) showing.<ref name=smithsonian/><ref>{{cite book|last=Herald|first=Earl Stannard|title=Living fishes of the world|publisher=Doubleday|year=1961|page=205|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=gbMMAQAAIAAJ}}</ref>

The egg mass (roe) is usually green, but may also be yellow, red, or brown. Pigment components [[bilin (biochemistry)|bilin]] and [[carotenoid]]s such as idoxanthin, crustaxanthin, and vitamin A2 [[aldehyde]] ([[Dehydroretinal|3-dehydroretinal]]). The bilin and [[retinal]] creates the base green color, and the amount of relative idoxanthin content is the determinant of the color variation. Since food sources such as the [[Amphipoda|amphipods]] and stomach contents reveal negligible traces of idoxanthin and crustaxanthin, they must be converted from the cartenoid [[astaxanthin]] that are abundant in their food. Researchers hypothesize that the intake of astaxanthin influences amount of idoxanthin produced and result in egg color changes.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Morioka|first1=T.(<U+68EE><U+5CA1><U+6CF0><U+4E09>)|last2=Hotta|first2=K.(<U+5800><U+7530><U+548C><U+592B>)|last3=Tomoda|first3=T.(<U+53CB><U+7530><U+52D9>)|last4=Nakamura|first4=L (<U+4E2D><U+6751><U+5F18><U+4E8C>)|title=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF>Arctoscopus japonicus<U+306E><U+5375><U+584A><U+304C><U+591A><U+8272><U+5316><U+3059><U+308B><U+8981><U+56E0> (A possible factor influencing the color variation in Japanese sandfish Arctoscopus japonicus egg masses)|journal=<U+65E5><U+672C><U+6C34><U+7523><U+5B66><U+4F1A><U+8A8C> (Journal of the Japanese Society of Fisheries Science|volume=71|number=2|year=2005|pages=212<U+2013>214|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/suisan/71/2/71_2_212/_article/-char/ja/}}</ref>

== Classification ==
In the current [[taxonomy]], the species is classified under the [[Perciformes]] (Perch-likes) order, [[Trachinoidei]] suborder, and [[Trichodontidae]] (sandfishes) family.  However, [[mitochondrial DNA]] analysis indicates that the species is more closely related to ''[[Cottus]]'' spp. of the [[Scorpaeniformes]] order.<ref>{{cite journal|ref=harv|author=<U+6C34><U+7523><U+7DCF><U+5408><U+7814><U+7A76><U+30BB><U+30F3><U+30BF><U+30FC>|authorlink=:ja:<U+6C34><U+7523><U+7DCF><U+5408><U+7814><U+7A76><U+30BB><U+30F3><U+30BF><U+30FC>|title=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+306E><U+30DF><U+30C8><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+30C9><U+30EA><U+30A2><U+FF24><U+FF2E><U+FF21><U+5168><U+5869><U+57FA><U+914D><U+5217><U+306E><U+6C7A><U+5B9A><U+3068><U+985E><U+7E01><U+95A2><U+4FC2><U+306E><U+89E3><U+660E>|journal=<U+6C34><U+7523><U+9031><U+5831>|number=1553|year=2001|month=August}} [http://www.fra.affrc.go.jp/pressrelease/pr13/130724hatahata/130724hatahata.htm Press release] [http://iss.ndl.go.jp/books/R000000004-I5874945-00?ar=4e1f NDL data]</ref>

=== Similar species ===
* Pacific sandfish, ''Trichodon trichodon'', or ''ezo hatahata'' in Japanese, found from the [[Aleutian Islands]] to [[Alaska]] down to [[California]].<ref name="shibata">{{cite journal|ref=harv|last=Shibata|first=Satoru (<U+67F4><U+7530><U+7406>)|title=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+3068><U+30A8><U+30BE><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+306E><U+6BD4><U+8F03>|journal=<U+65E5><U+672C><U+6D77><U+30D6><U+30ED><U+30C3><U+30AF><U+8A66><U+9A13><U+7814><U+7A76><U+9332>|volume=29|year=1993|pages=17<U+2013>21|url=http://jsnfri.fra.affrc.go.jp/publication/shuuroku/shuuroku-29,17-21.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|ref=harv|last=Okiyama|first=M|title=Contrast in Reproductive Style Between Two Species of Sandfish (Family Trichodontidae)|journal=Fishery Bulletin U.S.|volume=88|year=1990|pages=543<U+2013>549}}</ref>

== Nomenclature ==
The Japanese name ''hatahata'' may be written as [[wikt:<U+9C30>|<U+9C30>]], which consists of the fish radical [[wikt:<U+9B5A>|<U+9B5A>]] combined with the character {{nihongo||<U+795E>|kami|extra2="god"}}. Shokusanjin ([[<U+014C>ta Nampo]]) records the lore that it came to be written this way "because within its scales arises the pattern of [[Mt. Fuji]], and was celebrated as auspicious fish," though the actual species has no scales.<ref><U+8700><U+5C71><U+4EBA><U+300E><U+4E00><U+8A71><U+4E00><U+8A00><U+300F><U+5DFB><U+5341><U+4E00>{{citation|last=<U+5927><U+7530>|first=<U+5357><U+755D>|title=<U+8700><U+5C71><U+4EBA><U+5168><U+96C6>|volume=4|publisher=<U+5409><U+5DDD><U+5F18><U+6587><U+9928>|year=1907|page=291|url=https://archive.org/details/shokusanjinzensh04tana}}<U+300C><U+9C57><U+306E><U+4E2D><U+306B><U+5BCC><U+58EB><U+5C71><U+306E><U+3082><U+3084><U+3046><U+3092><U+751F><U+3058><U+5019><U+6545><U+3001><U+3081><U+3067><U+305F><U+304D><U+9B5A><U+3068><U+795D><U+3057><U+3001><U+6587><U+5B57><U+306F><U+3044><U+3064><U+3054><U+308D><U+3088><U+308A><U+304B><U+9B5A><U+7BC7><U+306B><U+795E><U+3068><U+66F8><U+306A><U+308A><U+3001><U+300D></ref>

An alternate Japanese name is {{nihongo||<U+96F7><U+9B5A>|kaminari-uwo|extra2="thunder fish"}}, which come from the fact that its spawning (and catching) season coincides with the months when thunderstorms frequently occur.<ref name="lowry">{{citation|last=Lowry|first=Dave|title=The Connoisseur's Guide to Sushi|publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com|year=2010|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0ut9nOwsFegC|pages=116<U+2013>118|isbn=1458764141}}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Nihon D<U+014D>butsu Gakkai|title=Annotationes Zoologic<U+00E6> Japonenses|volume=1|place=Tokyo|year=1897|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=VTtMAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA108|page=108}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ashburne|first1=John|last2=Abe|first2=Yoshi|title=Japan|publisher=Lonely Planet|year=2002|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=KSu3inWoJloC&pg=PT6|page=51}}</ref> In fact, ''hatahata'' is an old [[onomatopoeia]] representing the sound of the thunderclap, whose use is attested in the 10th century ''Kager<U+014D> Nikki'', and which is the root of the verb ''hatata-ku'' "to thunder."<ref name="lowry"/><ref>{{citation|editor-last1=Mozume|editor-first1= Takayo (<U+7269><U+96C6><U+9AD8><U+4E16>)|editor-last2=Yokoi|editor-first2=Tokifuyu (<U+6A2A><U+4E95><U+6642><U+51AC>)|contribution=<U+652F><U+8A00><U+8003>|work=K<U+014D>ten K<U+014D>ky<U+016B>jo k<U+014D>en (<U+7687><U+5178><U+8B1B><U+7A76><U+6240><U+8B1B><U+6F14>)|volume=15|number=148|page=12|publisher=<U+7687><U+5178><U+8B1B><U+7A76><U+6240>|year=1895|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=49QtAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA55}}</ref>

In the {{ill2|Akita dialect|ja|<U+79CB><U+7530><U+5F01>}}, ''hataha'' sounds like ''hadahada'' to non-natives, because the "''ta''" is locally pronounded in [[Aspirated consonant|voiced]] [[Aspirated consonant|unaspirated]] {{ill2|dakuon{{!}}''dakuon''|ja|<U+6FC1><U+97F3>}}, so that ''hadahada'' is sometimes listed as a local name for the fish.<ref>{{citation|last=<U+6F81><U+6FA4>|first=<U+656C><U+4E09>|title=<U+65E5><U+672C><U+9B5A><U+540D><U+96C6><U+89BD><U+3000><U+7B2C><U+4E8C><U+90E8>|publisher=<U+751F><U+6D3B><U+793E>|year=1944|page=175}}</ref> In Akita, the fish sometimes bears the name "''satake uo''" after the [[Satake clan]] who were rules of the land around [[1600]]. But the Satakes were originally rooted in [[Hitachi Province]] (present-day [[Ibaraki Prefecture]]), and legend has it that the fish followed the masters from the old country (Shokusanjin notes that the legend is given in the {{nihongo|<U+79CB><U+7530><U+6749><U+76F4><U+7269><U+8A9E>|Akita Suginaoshi monogatari|}}).<ref name="lowry"/><ref>{{Harvnb|<U+5927><U+7530>|1907|loc=vol.4, p.291}}</ref>{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|Lowry explains the name stuck after the success of the Satake clan's success at exporting the fish as fertilizer.<ref name="lowry"/>}} In [[Tottori Prefecture]] it is called ''shirohata'' or ''kitaha''.{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|Lowry gives ''kihata''<ref name="lowry"/> as do some Japanese source, but ''kitaha'' seems to be supported by the majority}}</ref><ref group="lower-alpha">Called ''shima aji'' in the vicinity of [[N<U+014D>, Niigata]], though this is misleading that term refers to the [[white trevally]] in mainstream Japan. ([http://books.google.com/books?id=XMPlAAAAMAAJ <U+6F01><U+6751><U+3068><U+5CF6> (2004), p.81])</ref>

== Fisheries  ==
The species is caught by [[bottom trawling]] offshore and by {{ill2|set-netting|ja|<U+5B9A><U+7F6E><U+7DB2>}} and [[gillnetting]] the coastal spawning waters.<ref name="masuda">{{cite book|last=Masuda|first=Hajime|title=The Fishes of the Japanese Archipelago|volume=1|publisher=Tokai University Press|year=1984 |url=http://books.google.co.jp/books?id=ZTRBAAAAYAAJ|page=221|isbn=4486050541}}</ref> The fish stock down further south are caught by [[Danish seine fishing]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Watanabe|Sakuramoto|Minami|Suzuki|2006|p=221}}</ref>

In Akita Prefecture, it was bought in bulk by the crates (5 or 10 crates at a time) when in season, and the excess would be preserved as salted fish or as [[nukazuke]] to be consumed as a [[protein]] source over the winter.<ref name="homma"/><ref>{{cite book|editor=<U+79CB><U+7530><U+5E02> (Japan)|title=<U+79CB><U+7530><U+5E02><U+53F2>|volume=16(<U+6C11><U+4FD7><U+7DE8>)|year=2003|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=130NAQAAMAAJ|page=300}} (Akita City's published municipal history, governmental publication)</ref>

[[FAO]] Statistics record that in 1950, the annual catch was 10,000 tons accounted solely in Japan, by the beginning of the 1970s Korean fisheries were catching half as much or more in tonnage as the Japanese. The global peak catch occurred in 1971 with 56,700 tons total, but by the end of the decade in 1979 there was a sharp collapse in the fish stock resulting in an annual catch of only 11,546 tons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fishbase.org/report/FAO/FAOCatchList.php?scientific=Arctoscopus+japonicus|title=FAO Capture Production of Arctoscopus japonicus (t)     n = 2 |author=fishbase|date=09/06/2010 |accessdate=April-2014}}</ref>{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|Akita Prefecture alone caught 15,000 tons per year at its peak.<ref name="akitadaihyakkajiten-hatahata" />}}

In Akita Prefecture, peak catch attained to 15,000 tons per year,<ref name="akitadaihyakkajiten-hatahata">{{citation|last=<U+7AF9><U+5185>|first=<U+5065>|contribution=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF>|work=<U+79CB><U+7530><U+5927><U+767E><U+79D1><U+4E8B><U+5178> (encyclopedia)|publisher=<U+79CB><U+7530><U+9B41><U+65B0><U+5831><U+793E>|year=1981|page=660}}</ref> but overfishing, possibly with an interplay of water temperature "regime" shifts, led to persisting depletion,<ref>{{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Watanabe|first1=Kyuji|last2=Sakuramoto|first2=Kazumi|last3=Sugiyama|first3=Hideki|last4=Suzuki|first4=Naoki|title=Collapse of the Arctoscopus japonicus Catch in the Sea of Japan<U+FF0D>Environmental Factors or Overfishing<U+FF0D>|journal=Global Environmental Res|volume=9|number=2|year=2005|pages=131&ndash;137|url=http://www.researchgate.net/publication/216505998_Collapse_of_the_Arctoscopus_japonicus_Catch_in_the_Sea_of_Japan_-_Environmental_Factors_or_Overfishing_-/file/9fcfd50bff8e9d26b7.pdf}}</ref> so that the fishermen of Akita Prefecture, led by its {{ill2|Fisherise Cooperative Association|ja|<U+6F01><U+696D><U+5354><U+540C><U+7D44><U+5408>}} self-imposed a total moratorium on the catch from 1992-1995<ref name="makino"/><ref>The fishery closure years are graphed in fig. 4, {{Harvnb|Watanabe|Sakuramoto|Sugiyama|Suzuki|2005}}</ref> In 1999, four participating prefectures formed a fisheries management organization<!--FMO-->to manage the fish stock, followed in 2003 by a formal Resource Recovery Plan (<U+8CC7><U+6E90><U+56DE><U+5FA9><U+8A08><U+753B>) for these prefectures.<ref name="makino"/> In Korea, the catch was 25,000 tons per year in 1971, but suffered a similar decline to 4,000 tons by 2008, and that country has also instituted conservation measures.<ref name="kim-lee-cha"/>

[[Tottori prefecture]] is another major catch harvest area. Whereas Akita targets egg-carrying adults approach the surface to spawn, Tottori fishing practices capture the deep water migrating populations by [[bottom trawling]], so that the caught fish tends to be fattier, though without eggs. The catch season for Tottori spans from September to May.<ref>{{Cite web |date= |url=http://www.pref.tottori.lg.jp/dd.aspx?menuid=206349 |title=<U+98DF><U+306E><U+307F><U+3084><U+3053><U+9CE5><U+53D6><U+770C>/<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF> |publisher=<U+9CE5><U+53D6><U+770C> |accessdate=2012-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date= |url=http://www.tottori-guide.jp/828/829/831/839/8377.html |title=<U+9CE5><U+53D6><U+770C><U+89B3><U+5149><U+6848><U+5185> <U+3068><U+3063><U+3068><U+308A><U+65C5><U+306E><U+751F><U+60C5><U+5831> |publisher=<U+793E><U+56E3><U+6CD5><U+4EBA> <U+9CE5><U+53D6><U+770C><U+89B3><U+5149><U+9023><U+76DF> |accessdate=2013-02-26}}</ref>

=== Fishing restrictions ===
* In [[1999]] the Aomori, Akita, Yamagata, and Niigata prefectures instituted restrictions prohibiting capture of fish measuring less than 15&nbsp;cm.<ref>{{Cite web |date= |url=http://www9.ocn.ne.jp/~atgyokyo/ |title=<U+6F01><U+5354><U+306E><U+30DA><U+30FC><U+30B8> |publisher=<U+79CB><U+7530><U+770C><U+6F01><U+696D><U+5354><U+540C><U+7D44><U+5408> |accessdate=2012-03-23}}</ref>
* Accidents and drownings involving sports fishermen going overboard<ref>{{Cite web |date= |url=http://www.police.pref.aomori.jp/syo/ajigasawa/chiiki.html |title=<U+9BF5><U+30F6><U+6CA2><U+8B66><U+5BDF><U+7F72> |publisher=[[<U+9752><U+68EE><U+770C><U+8B66><U+5BDF>]] |accessdate=2012-03-23}}</ref> as well as poaching egg masses (scavenging eggs washed ashore also constitute poaching)<ref name="mutsusinpou">{{Cite news|url = http://www.mutusinpou.co.jp/news/2008/11/4436.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100322232650/www.mutusinpou.co.jp/news/2008/11/4436.html|title = <U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+306E><U+30D6><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+5BC6><U+6F01><U+9632><U+3054><U+3046><U+3000><U+9BF5><U+30B1><U+6CA2><U+6F01><U+5354><U+306A><U+3069><U+547C><U+3073><U+639B><U+3051>|newspaper = [[<U+9678><U+5965><U+65B0><U+5831>]]|archivedate=22 Mar 2010 23:26:50|publisher = [[<U+9678><U+5965><U+65B0><U+5831><U+793E>]]|date = 2008-11-28|accessdate = 2009-11-16}}</ref> has prompted regulations and patrolling efforts by the {{ill2|Japanese fisheries cooperative{{!}}fisheries cooperative|ja|<U+6F01><U+696D><U+5354><U+540C><U+7D44><U+5408>}} and police.<ref name="mutsusinpou" /><ref>{{Cite web |date= |url=http://www.pref.aomori.lg.jp/sangyo/agri/suisan_yugyo_hatahata.html |title=<U+9752><U+68EE><U+770C><U+6C34><U+7523><U+60C5><U+5831><U+FF08><U+904A><U+6F01><U+3092><U+697D><U+3057><U+3080><U+7686><U+69D8><U+3078><U+FF1E><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+904A><U+6F01><U+8005><U+306E><U+7686><U+3055><U+3093><U+3078><U+FF09> |publisher=[[<U+9752><U+68EE><U+770C>]] |accessdate=2012-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2011-09-01 |url=http://www.pref.akita.lg.jp/www/contents/1162943900070/index.html |title=<U+306F><U+305F><U+306F><U+305F><U+904A><U+6F01><U+8005><U+306E><U+307F><U+306A><U+3055><U+307E><U+3078> |publisher=[[<U+79CB><U+7530><U+770C>]] |accessdate=2012-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date= |url=http://www.pref.yamagata.jp/ou/967001/30cf30bf30cf30bf306e63a1635565b96cd5898f5236.pdf |title=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+306E><U+63A1><U+6355><U+65B9><U+6CD5><U+898F><U+5236> |format=PDF |publisher=[[<U+5C71><U+5F62><U+770C>]] |accessdate=2012-03-23}}</ref><U+3002>
** Foraging, possessing and engagin in sales of egg masses are prohibited (Aomori and Akita)
** Fishing method restrictions (Aomori, Akita, Yamagata)

== Uses ==
At one time, dried hatahata was one type of fish-based fertilizer (fish manure) being trafficked in Japan.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kellner|first=O.|title=Researches on Composition of several Japanese Fertilizers|journal=Bulletin of the Imperial Colledge of Agriculture|year=1889|number=4|page=6|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=szNHAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA6}}</ref><ref group="lower-alpha">Statistics for quantities entering the Tokyo Market indicate over 15,000 ''hy<U+014D>'' were shipped in 1903, but none during the other years from 1902 ~ 1911. Each ''hy<U+014D>'' (straw bag) contained 8 ~ 4 [[sh<U+014D> (unit)|sh<U+014D>]]. {{cite book|title=<U+6771><U+4EAC><U+5546><U+696D><U+4F1A><U+8B70><U+6240><U+7D71><U+8A08><U+5E74><U+5831>|year=1924|url=http://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/931873|pages=34<U+2013>35}}</ref>

=== Food ingredient ===
[[File:Hatahata.JPG|280px|thumb|Dried ''himono'' or [[stockfish]] of hatahata]]
[[File:Sailfin sandfish ekiben in Akita Station by woinary.jpg|200px|thumb|An [[ekiben]] sold at [[Akita Station]] serves the fish [[chirashi sushi]] style.]]

The fish lacks [[Fish scale|scale]], has few small bones, and the spine separates easily from the flesh, so that they are usually poached or broiled whole, or just with the head off. If the fish is fresh, snapping the bone at the base of the tail beforehand, will make it easier for the spine to come off easily after broiling.
Fresh ''hatahata'' can be served salted and broiled, or be poached in a pot flavored with [[soy sauce]], [[sakekasu]], but especially [[shottsuru]] in Akita the pot dish would be flavored with [[shottsuru]], a fish sauce traditionally made by fermented the fish cured in brine.<ref name="homma">{{cite book|last=Homma|first=Gaku|title=The Folk Art of Japanese Country Cooking: A Traditional Diet for Today's World|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=HZRDsVUZufoC&pg=PA69|publisher=North Atlantic Books|year=1991|isbn=1556430981|page=69}}</ref>

Another preparation is the {{ill2|misodengaku{{!}}''dengaku''|ja|<U+5473><U+564C><U+7530><U+697D>}} (slathered with sweet miso paste and broiled),<ref name="n-journal">{{cite journal|title=<U+3081><U+3044><U+3076><U+3064><U+79CB><U+7530><U+770C>|journal=<U+65E5><U+672C><U+8A9E><U+30B8><U+30E3><U+30FC><U+30CA><U+30EB>|date=2007-11-15|url=http://books.google.co.jp/books?id=htY1AQAAIAAJ|page=40}}</ref> which is eaten not only in Akita but also in the {{ill2|Sh<U+014D>nai region|ja|<U+5E84><U+5185><U+5730><U+65B9>}} around [[Sakata, Yamagata]].

The fish is preserved in various ways, such as ''[[nukazuke]]'' (pickled in rice bran and salt),<ref name="homma"/> ''[[stockfish|himono]]'' (as dried fish),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crd.ndl.go.jp/reference/detail?page=ref_view&id=1000085813|title=<U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+306E><U+5E72><U+7269><U+306E><U+5E02><U+5834><U+898F><U+6A21><U+3092><U+77E5><U+308A><U+305F><U+3044>|date=2011-04-20|accessdate=April-2013}} (FAQ published by Tottori Prefecture Library. Questioner sought market size of hatahata himono. No exact statistice was available, but the answerer quoted [[Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications]]'s household budge survey that in 2006 the average household spent 15,835 yen, and that for fish in general, dried fish accouted for 59.3% of consumption.</ref> as {{ill2|mirinboshi{{!}}''mirinboshi''|ja|<U+307F><U+308A><U+3093><U+5E72><U+3057>}}, ([[mirin]]-based flavored dried fish) {{cite journal|title= <U+30CF><U+30BF><U+30CF><U+30BF><U+307F><U+308A><U+3093><U+5E72><U+306B><U+3064><U+3044><U+3066>|journal=<U+5175><U+5EAB><U+770C><U+7ACB><U+6C34><U+7523><U+8A66><U+9A13><U+5834><U+4E8B><U+696D><U+5831><U+544A> (Bulletin of the Hyogo Prefectural Fisheries Experimental Station)|year=1965|pages=133<U+2013>136|url=http://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/2520606}} It is also made into a preserved ''[[narezushi]]''; in Akita the preserving medium consists of rice and koji (''[[Aspergillus oryzae]]'' mold for brewing [[sake]])<ref name="lowry"/><ref name="homma"/> but in [[Tottori Prefecture]], {{ill2|Shirohatazushi{{!}}''shirohatazushi''|ja|<U+3057><U+308D><U+306F><U+305F><U+305A><U+3057>}} and uses ''[[Okara (food)|okara]]'' (soy pulp).<ref>{{citation|last=<U+6210><U+702C>|first=<U+5B87><U+5E73>|title=47<U+90FD><U+9053><U+5E9C><U+770C><U+30FB><U+9B5A><U+98DF><U+6587><U+5316><U+767E><U+79D1>|publisher=<U+4E38><U+5584><U+51FA><U+7248>|year=2011|pages=183, 275}}</ref><ref><U+65E5><U+672C><U+306E><U+98DF><U+751F><U+6D3B><U+5168><U+96C6><U+9CE5><U+53D6><U+7DE8><U+96C6><U+59D4><U+54E1><U+4F1A><U+7DE8><U+3001><U+300E><U+65E5><U+672C><U+306E><U+98DF><U+751F><U+6D3B><U+5168><U+96C6>31<U+3000><U+805E><U+304D><U+66F8><U+9CE5><U+53D6><U+306E><U+98DF><U+4E8B><U+300F>p24<U+3001>p56<U+3001>1991<U+5E74><U+3001><U+6771><U+4EAC><U+3001><U+793E><U+56E3><U+6CD5><U+4EBA><U+8FB2><U+5C71><U+6F01><U+6751><U+6587><U+5316><U+5354><U+4F1A><U+3001>ISBN 4-540-91003-5</ref>

Fresh ''hatahata'' is suitable for {{ill2|mizuni|{{!}''mizuni''ja|<U+6C34><U+716E>}} or poaching in water (the dish in [[Yamagata Prefecture|Yamagata]] is called ''yu-age''<ref>{{Harvnb|<U+6210><U+702C>|2011|p=79}}</ref>), and eaten with soy sauce.  It can be made into ''hatahata-jiru'' ([[miso soup]]), but the [[miso]] should be dissolved in the broth before the fish is plunged, otherwise the fish falls apart.

In [[South Korea]], the fish (known there as ''dorumuk'' ({{lang-ko|{{linktext|<U+B3C4>|<U+B8E8>|<U+BB35>}}}})) is eaten in communities in [[Gangwon Province (South Korea)|Gangwon Province]] and elsewhere along the [[Sea of Japan]] (which Koreans call "Donghae" or "East Sea"). In Korea it is mainly an ingredient for ''[[chige]]'' hot pot dishes, but sometimes the roe-laden females are grilled and eaten.<ref>{{Cite web|date=|url=http://talk.imbc.com/news/view.aspx?idx=32191|title=<U+BABB><U+C0DD><U+ACA8><U+B3C4> <U+B9DB><U+C740> <U+C77C><U+D488>! <<U+B3C4><U+B8E8><U+BB35> <U+C694><U+B9AC>> (Looks awful but tastes great" dorumuk cooking)|publisher=MBC Cultural Broadcasting|language=Korean|accessdate=2013-8-10}}</ref><U+3002>

=== Shottsuru ===
{{main|shottsuru}}
[[image:Gyosyou2830.JPG|200px|thumb|shottsuru]]

Locally, a [[fish sauce]] called ''[[shottsuru]]'' is made from this fish. The sauce which literally means "salty juice",<ref name="homma"/> is made by pickling and fermenting the salted fish, and straining out the debris. The fish sauce is used to flavor the ''shottsuru nabe'', or pot dish that uses this flavoring to cook the ''hatahata'' with vegetable and other ingredients.<ref name="lowry"/><ref name="homma"/> In the Akita dialect, the pot dish also sometimes called ''shottsuru kayaki'', with "{{ill2|mizuni|{{!}''kayaki''ja|<U+304B><U+3084><U+304D>}}" being the local term for [[nabebono]] or hot pot dish.

=== Roe ===
In the {{ill2|Akita ben|ja|<U+79CB><U+7530><U+5F01>}} dialect, the roe of this species is called ''buriko''.<ref name="n-journal"/> The fish is caught during its spawning season, when many of the females are loaded with eggs 2&ndash;3mm in diameter. The eggs are surrounded by slimy [[mucous]].

Fresh roe that is cooked will burst and make light popping sounds when eaten, but roe from the fish preserved in salt or miso turn rubbery and hard to chew, resulting in a more blunt sound that sounds like ''buri buri'' which resulted in its name.{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|There are alternate etymologies for ''buriko''. One theory is that the mucous covered eggs bind together and are hard to separate, leading to the name {{nihongo||''buriko''|<U+4E0D><U+96E2><U+5B50>|"unseparable children"}}. Another theory proposes that during the [[Edo Period]] when collecting the eggs was prohibited, a forager evaded an official's interrogation saying they were the eggs of ''buri'' ([[yellowtail]]).<ref name="akitadaihyakkajiten-buriko">{{citation|last=<U+5BCC><U+6728>|first=<U+9686><U+8535>|contribution=<U+30D6><U+30EA><U+30B3>|work=<U+79CB><U+7530><U+5927><U+767E><U+79D1><U+4E8B><U+5178> (encyclopedia)|publisher=<U+79CB><U+7530><U+9B41><U+65B0><U+5831><U+793E>|year=1981|page=714}}</ref>}}

In the ''miny<U+014D>'' folk ballad {{ill2|Akita ondo|ja|<U+79CB><U+7530><U+97F3><U+982D>}}, the [[Oga Peninsula|Oga]] de Oga buriko" in the lyrics refers to the roe. 
{{-}}

